<section xml:id="section-activity-clo14">
  <title>Activity for CLO-14</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo14-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p> 
          What is an iterated derivative?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An iterated derivative is the process of repeating
          differentiation. The outcome of a derivative is still a
          function, so I can differentiate again. Differentiation can
          be iterated. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a higher derivative?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A higher derivative is the output of iterated
          differentiation. A second derivative is the output of taking
          two derivatives. A third derivative is the output of taking
          three derivatives. This naming convention continues. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In what was is acceleration a higher derivative. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If <m>p(t)</m> is a position function, then the rate of
          change of position is velocity, si <m>p^\prime (t)</m>
          measures velocity. But acceleration is the rate of change of
          velocity, so it is a second derivative. <m>p^{\prime
          \prime}(t) </m> measures acceleration.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is damped harmonic motion?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Damped harmonic motion is a differential equation involving
          three term. It models a mass on a spring, or some other
          similar system where oscillation is possible. It has
          position, which is multiplied by a constant measuring the
          stiffness of the harmonic system.  It has velocity, the
          first derivative, which is multiplied by a constant
          measuring the strength of the friction in the system. Is
          has accelration, the second derivative, which is multiplied
          by a constant measuring the mass of the system. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-higher-derivatives">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Higher Derivatives</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this derivative.
          <md>
            \frac{d^2}{dx^2} 5x^4 - 7x^3 + 15x + 1 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need to take the derivative twice. Both times I am
          taking polynomial derivatives, so I am using linearity and
          the power rule for the derivatives. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^2}{dx^2} 5x^4 - 7x^3 + 15x + 1 \amp = \frac{d}{dx}
              \frac{d}{dx} 5x^4 - 7x^3 + 15x + 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} 20x^3 - 21x^2 + 15 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 60x^2 - 42x 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this derivative.
          <md>
            \frac{d^3}{dx^3} e^{4x}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need to take the derivative three times. Each time, this
          is a chain rule derivative, with outside function <m>e^u</m>
          and inside function <m>4x</m>. Each time the derivative of
          the inside produces a constant 4, which I can factor out of
          the remaining steps due to linearity. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^3}{dx^3} e^{4x} \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx}
              \frac{d}{du} e^u \Bigg|_{u = 4x} \frac{d}{dx} 4x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} e^u \Bigg|_{u = 4x} 4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} e^{4x} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{du} e^{u} \Bigg|_{u=4x}
              \frac{d}{dx} 4x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 \frac{d}{dx} e^{u} \Bigg|_{u=4x} 4 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 16 \frac{d}{dx} e^{4x}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 16 \frac{d}{du} e^{u} \Bigg|_{u=4x} \frac{d}{dx} 4x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 16 e^{u} \Bigg|_{u=4x} 4 = 64 e^{4x} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate this derivative.
          <md>
            \frac{d^4}{dx^4} \sin x - \cos x 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I have four derivatives to take. In each step, I use
          linearity and the known derivatives of sine and cosine.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^4}{dx^4} \sin x - \cos x \amp = \frac{d}{dx}
              \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \sin x - \cos x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \cos x + \sin x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} \cos x + \sin x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} \frac{d}{dx} -\sin x + \cos x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{d}{dx} -\cos x - \sin x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \sin x - \cos x 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Notice that I return to the original expression. That is as
          expected, since the fourth derivative of both sine and
          cosine is the same as whichever I started with. This
          subtraction of one from the other also has the property of
          being preserved under four derivatives, since the derivative
          respects subtraction. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
